book identifies the central role of the imagination in the philosophy of Peirce, a role often overlooked in analytic treatments of his thought. The final chapters pursue the observation made by Kant and Peirce that imaginative genius is a type of natural gift (ingenium) and must in some way be continuous with the creative force of nature. It makes this final turn by way of contemporary studies of metaphor, embodied cognition, and cognitive neuroscience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAesthetics. 0aCognition. 0aImagination (Philosophy). 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aScience Studies. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh  aAbduction.  aAesthetics.  aCognitive Neuroscience.  aContinuity.  aCreativity.  aEthics.  aImagination.  aKant.  aPeirce.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z97831111896040 cprintz978082325493440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823254958?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823254958423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823254958/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK